.TH PORTS 1 "2025-06-19" "scriptorium" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
ports \- show what processes are listening on which ports
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ports
.RB [ \-h | \-\-help ]
.RB [ \-v | \-\-verbose ]
.RB [ \-a | \-\-all ]
.RB [ \-k | \-\-kill ]
.RB [ \-f | \-\-force ]
.RB [ \-\-pid ]
.RB [ \-p | \-\-protocol
.IR protocol ]
.RI [ port ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B ports
shows information about processes listening on network ports. It can display all listening ports or focus on a specific port number. The utility can also terminate processes listening on specified ports.

By default, when given a port number, it shows which process is listening on that port and outputs the process name to stderr and formatted port information to stdout.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Show all listening ports instead of a specific port. When used, no port number should be specified.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Show verbose output with additional details including protocol, address, and command information.
.TP
.BR \-k ", " \-\-kill
Kill the process(es) listening on the specified port. Uses SIGTERM by default for graceful shutdown.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
When used with
.BR \-\-kill ,
uses SIGKILL (force kill) instead of SIGTERM. This immediately terminates the process without allowing cleanup.
.TP
.BR \-\-pid
Output only process IDs, one per line. Useful for scripting and piping to other commands.
.TP
.BR \-p " " \fIprotocol\fR, " \-\-protocol " \fIprotocol\fR
Specify the protocol to check. Valid values are
.I tcp
or
.IR udp .
Defaults to tcp if not specified.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Show help message and exit.
.SH ARGUMENTS
.TP
.I port
Port number to check (1-65535). Required unless using
.BR \-\-all .
.SH OUTPUT FORMAT
The default output shows:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Process names to stderr (for original script compatibility)
.IP \(bu 2
Formatted table with PID, process name, and port to stdout
.RE

In verbose mode, additional columns show:
.RS
.IP \(bu 2
Protocol (TCP/UDP)
.IP \(bu 2
Listening address
.IP \(bu 2
Full command line
.RE

When using
.BR \-\-pid ,
only process IDs are output to stdout, one per line.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
ports 3000
Show what process is listening on port 3000.
.TP
ports --all
Show all processes listening on any port.
.TP
ports -v 8080
Show verbose information about port 8080.
.TP
ports --pid 3000 | xargs kill
Get PID for port 3000 and kill the process.
.TP
ports --kill 8080
Gracefully terminate the process on port 8080.
.TP
ports --kill --force 3000
Force kill the process on port 3000.
.TP
ports -p udp 53
Show what's listening on UDP port 53 (DNS).
.TP
ports --protocol tcp --all
Show all TCP listening ports.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Success
.TP
1
Argument error (invalid port, missing arguments, etc.)
.TP
2
No process found on specified port
.TP
3
Error killing process
.TP
4
Missing required tools (lsof not available)
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.B ports
requires the following external tools:
.TP
.B lsof
For listing open files and network connections
.TP
.B ps
For process information (used when killing processes)
.TP
.B kill
For terminating processes (when using --kill option)
.SH NOTES
.PP
The tool uses
.B lsof
internally to gather port information. On some systems, lsof may require special permissions to show information about processes owned by other users.

.PP
When killing processes, the tool first attempts graceful termination with SIGTERM unless
.B \-\-force
is specified. After sending SIGTERM, it waits briefly and checks if the process is still running.

.PP
Multiple processes can listen on the same port (e.g., with SO_REUSEPORT). The tool will show and can kill all processes listening on the specified port.

.PP
The output format is designed to be both human-readable and script-friendly. Process names are sent to stderr to maintain compatibility with the original script behavior, allowing the main output to be piped while still showing context.
.SH SECURITY CONSIDERATIONS
.PP
Be careful when using the
.B \-\-kill
option, especially with
.BR \-\-force .
Always verify which process you're about to terminate.

.PP
The tool may require elevated privileges to see or kill processes owned by other users.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR lsof (8),
.BR netstat (8),
.BR ss (8),
.BR kill (1),
.BR ps (1)
